06468nam a22009375i 9781487574451DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191977onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875744517 a10.3138/97814875744512doi  a(DE-B1597)536852  a(OCoLC)1129209038  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aE99.T56bD46 1977eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a323.1/19/70719300aDene Nation :bThe colony within /ced. by Mel Watkins. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1977  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tForeword -- tContents -- tPreface -- tThe Dene Speak -- tDene Declaration -- tI Statements to the Mackenzie Valley Pipeline Inquiry -- tII Statements to the Mackenzie Valley Pipeline Inquiry -- tStatements to the Mackenzie Valley Pipeline Inquiry -- tResources -- tThe Mapping Project -- tA Trapper's Life -- tCountry Food -- tThe Dene Economy -- tThe Loss of Economic Rents -- tThe Distribution of Economic Benefits from a Pipeline -- tFrom Underdevelopment to Development -- tRights -- tThe Colonial Experience -- tThe Political System and the Dene -- tColonialism in the Communities -- tThe Schools -- tAboriginal Rights -- tThe Dene Nation and Confederation -- tConclusions -- tWe the Dene -- tA Proposal to the Government and People of Canada -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of papers by some twenty contributors has been selected in the main from presentations made up to the Berger Inquiry, and reflects the efforts of the Dene people to block the construction of a pipeline through the Mackenzie Valley lands they claim as their own. The issue is broader than a pipeline or even a land claim, and the presentations go well beyond showing the adverse effects of a pipeline, serious though these may be, and beyond asserting an Aboriginal claim to the land, valid though that may be. Rather, they reflect the Dene nation’s fundamental perception that their struggle is for the most universal of human rights, the right to be a self-determining people, living with their land as they have always done. Should no pipeline ever materialize up the Mackenzie Valley, the Dene nation will continue to assert this right and continue to strive for decolonization in matters of economics, politics, education, law, and culture. The papers, some of them written by Dene and others by specialists in a variety of fields, reveal the profound issues of human rights from which the pipeline protest ultimately derives. This book is essential reading for all concerned with Canada’s future as a compassionate democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aTinne IndiansxGovernment relations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAsch, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnaby, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBean, Wilf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, Phillip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheezie, Gerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErasmus, Georges, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelliwell, John F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJelliss, Arvin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKakfwi, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurszewski, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a